Data-Mining Project Write-Up

Executive Summary

This report provides an analysis and evaluation of 424 UberEats deliveries made by our

group member over the course of 6 months from June to December of 2021 in both the Upper Eastside Seattle and Greater San Diego area. The methods of analysis include exploratory analysis of the trip data by answering questions of data distribution, variable correlation and relationships, how strong those relationships are, and what these discoveries mean using the ggplot2 package in R. Further, the analysis also includes solving data queries that provide a deeper understanding into some of the patterns that exist in the data. All calculations can be found in the R code uploaded to the group repository. The results of the data analyzed show

The data was pulled from the UberEats Driver app, and manually inputted into an excel

spreadsheet for analysis. The variables pulled are from each individual trip over the 6 month period including: Date, Day of Week, Time the order was started, the Final Pay of the trip, the Est Pay of the trip, the Tip included, the Promotion offered by UberEats algorithm on the trip (based on location and demand at that particular time), the trips flat Fare, Pickup Location, Drop-off Location, the Distance traveled in miles, and the Duration of time the trip took in minutes. Two additional variables that require further explanation are the # of Trips and Additional Pay. The # of Trips represents whether one or two drop-offs were made within that one trip - by trip meaning the calculated fare, promotion, and final pay were all included in one calculation, even if two trips were made from one location - thus, when tip and final pay is calculated from a 2-drop-off trip, it is the sum of both orders. Then, Additional Pay was an additional calculated variable that was input into the raw data that subtracts the Final Pay by the Est Pay. Within the UberEats app, customers have the opportunity to pre-select a tip amount, but if they felt the delivery service provided went above and beyond expectations, they can go back into the app and add additional tips, hence the variables Est Pay being the originally calculated pay with the initial tip, and the Additional Pay representing the extra tip that a customer may have added. The reason why there are many Null values in the month of June for Est. Pay and Additional Pay was because this tip-addition update wasn't implemented until July of 2020. Before then, customers just added their tips after they got their food ordered.

Finally, in introducing the data preparation for analysis, the raw data

(BUAN_370_UberEats_Raw_Data_1) was split - or parsed - into two datasets: BUAN370_UberEats_Main_Data and BUAN370_UberEats_Fare_Data joined at the added primary key Trip ID in the BUAN370_UberEats_Main_Data - shortened to Main in pre processing - and the foreign key Trip ID in the BUAN370_UberEats_Fare_Data - shortened to Fare in pre-processing. The Fare dataset was parsed from the Main to include all the payment variables including: Final Pay, Est Pay, Additional Pay, Tip, Promotion, and Fare.

Cleaning the Data

After parsing the data into excel, the data was already well-cleaned and prepared, due to

the process of manual data-collection. Still, there were a few simple steps to remove. For example, Removing null observations, renaming the variables without spaces, and cleaning the Time attribute in order to make the data TIDY for analysis.

The first step in cleaning the data was to rename the variables. The purpose of the

renaming was to remove the spaces in the variables to be able to run the queries. For instance, the variable Trip ID was renamed to TripID. ( names(BUAN370_UberEats_Main_Data)[1] < 'TripID'). The cleaning of the variables was done for every variable in both of the datasets.

In order to remove the null rows we removed any row if the date variable had an NA

value in it. If an observation in the date variable had a NA value then there were no deliveries made for that day. In order to clean these rows only we used the code ( Main < Main[!is.na(Main$Date), ]

View(Main) ).

The last step in cleaning the data was to clean the Time variable. When the data was

imported into R, the date of the time of day was December 31, 1899. In order to remove this date we subbed the date with a space so that there was no longer a date available leaving just the time of the delivery. The code used in the dataset to complete this was sub('1899-12-31',' ',Main$Time).

Analysis

Visualizations

Visualization 1: Final Pay Over Duration Of Trip (Line Chart)

Using the ggplot(), geom_line(), and geom_smooth() functions, we created a

visualization of our group members Final Pay based on the duration of his UberEats' Trips. The data is very volatile, so using the geom_smooth allowed us to see the trend between Final Pay and Duration. As one would expect, the longer the trip it the greater the average final pay.

Visualization 2: Average Promotion Per Day (Pie Chart)

To get the data of average promotion per day, we first created a query that would hold the

exact data we were looking to display. Pulling and averaging the promotion and grouping by weekday accomplished this. This information was stored using the sqldf() function on the query and creating a new variable called Pie. Another label was created to display the name of the weekday as well as its respective payment. Using the pie() function to visualize these labels and queries we were better able to see which days on average had the most incentive attached to them. From the chart it is clear that Sunday, Monday, and Saturday are the most popular days for promotions.

Visualization 3: Average Pay Per Trip (Box Plot)

The boxplot visualization was created to visualize the expected pay per trip, on average,

over the entire data set of our group members UberEats service. Using just the boxplot() function, we created this relatively easily. The average pay for a trip was ~$13. With the Interquartile Range in between $9 and $15. It is also obvious that there are many outliers outside the whiskers, ranging well above $50. This helps represent the expectation one could have when looking at the payment of an UberEats driver, as well as show how many trips can provide a much more lucrative amount of money, albeit infrequently.

Visualization 4: Distance and Duration compared to Final Pay

The bubble chart visualization was created to visualize the final pay amount received compared to how long and how far he drove for each trip. In the bubble chart we can see that the bigger the bubble the more money he received for that trip. Also, the longer time and distance it takes to complete the trip then the more money he should receive. For example, there are bigger bubbles farther out in the chart rather than in the short distance.

Visualization 5: Average tip per Day

In this visualization it shows the average tip per day on a bar graph. This was a relatively easy visualization as it is just graphing the two different variables. This visualization can show the driver Matt that he is more likely to receive a bigger tip on Sundays rathers than any of the other days of the week. The second highest day of the week was Friday. Another aspect of the query was to be able to display the days in order.

Visualization 6: Average Final pay vsAverage Estimated pay by month

The sixth and last visualization is a box and line chart that compares the final pay to the estimated pay each month he drove. In this visualization a month was removed from the data because the month of June had all null values for estimated pay. The estimated pay was not recorded. Each month the average final pay was higher than the estimated pay. In the month of November, the estimated pay was almost just the same or higher than the average final pay. The goal for Matt is to always have the final pay be higher than the estimated pay.

Queries

Query 1: Introduction to Variables

We also ran several queries to better understand the patterns in our data. In order of

queries, our first query - Query 1 - we simply introduced all of our variables as a simple introductory query:

u

Query 2: Highest Paying Weekend Trips

Query 2 ranks our trips by pay, allowing us to see the 15 highest paying trips. What we

are able to recognize here is that, first, most of the highest paying trips tend to be on Sundays and Fridays, demonstrating that working on the weekends tends to yield the most money made. Also, the tips are almost all $20 or more, showing that the reason these tips are so high-paying is due to the extra large tips more than any other factor (like promotion or fare).

Query 3: Days of the Week with the Highest Average Pay

Based on Query 2, we thought it would be interesting to rank the days of the week with

the highest average pay. According to the query, we are able to see that, yes, in fact, the weekends do tend to yield the highest average pay. What is interesting to note here is that Saturdays, however, do have the second lowest average pay, but this may be because it has the lowest number of trips taken, so the body of work may be too small to be representative of what other drivers tend to make on Saturday.

Query 4 & 5: Highest Paying Trips on a Weekend and Weekday

Following Query 3, we decided to take a look at the single, highest paying trips on a

weekend and weekday. Although this may not look to yield a significant discovery, it is helpful in understanding the max capacity that our group member has, and even trying to break that record for the highest amount earned on one trip.

Query 6 and 7: Trips With Additional Pay

Queries 6 and 7 provide insight into the number of times that additional tip was given

after delivery. Its rather surprising to see that 119 times (Query 6) out of 278 eligible trips (Query 7) additional tips were added after delivery. That means that over 40% of the trips taken received additional tips. A large reason for this is because our group member would add a thank you note, paired with an Andes chocolate to every delivery order, so people would often add tips of appreciation for the gesture.

Query 8, 9 and 10: Average Pay, Promotion and Tip Based on Pickup Location

Queries 8, 9 and 10 begin to look at location, specifically which pickup locations tend to

yield the highest average pay. A few interesting patterns to note here is that the highest average pay and tip tended to be in neighborhoods in WA, whereas the highest promotions tended to be in San Diego. More specifically, there isnt much overlap between the average pay and tip queries (Queries 8 and 10) compared to the promotion query (Query 9), when one may guess that there would be. Thus, again showing that tip has the greatest influence on final pay rather than promotion. Another interesting thing to note is that promotions seem to be higher in the city as most of the top 10 average promotion neighborhoods are closer to downtown, whether in Seattle or San Diego, whereas final pay and tips tend to be higher in suburban neighborhoods. (Important to note here that this takes further understanding of both areas in order to come to this understanding)

Query 11: Average Pay and Tip based on Drop-off Location

Following Queries 8-10, we also took a look at the Drop-off Locations with the highest

average pay and tip as well. Here, we similarly noticed that both the highest tips and final pay tended to be from neighborhoods far removed from highly populated areas or downtown. (Again, this takes some previous understanding of the neighborhoods to recognize) Its interesting to note this, as customers tend to sympathize with the long drive and give larger tips for this reason.

Query 12 and 13: Average Distance and Duration based on Drop-off and Pick-up Locations

Following the location theme, Queries 12 and 13 ranks the average trip duration and

distance for each neighborhood pickup and drop-off. To no surprise, the main pattern to be drawn from these observations is that all of the neighborhoods are far-removed from either downtown San Diego, or downtown Seattle, Redmond or Bellevue, oftentimes out east in both cases. Its also interesting to see that there is an exactly equal representation of neighborhoods in San Diego and WA. One thing to note is that when pickups happen in Sammamish, although its somewhat of a hot-spot for pickups (13 trips started there), the trips tended to be dispersed pretty far to other neighborhoods (Avg Distance of 6.75 miles), so that may be an area to avoid to maximize drive-time and trip-maximization.

Query 14: Total Pay, Additional Pay, Tip and Promotion

For the last and final Query 14, we simply wanted to calculate what the total pay received across all 424 observations was. Although there are not many patterns to draw here, it is interesting to see that of the $5,702.28 earned, 8.1% ($463.06) was earned from additional tips added after delivery, 46.7% ($2,664.77) was earned from total tips, and only 6.4% ($367.04) was earned from promotional pay.

Conclusion

Throughout this project we were able to pull various conclusions about the data, and

identify trends within the food delivery service industry in regards to our group members experience. However, something we became aware of when sifting through the data and coming up with ideas for queries and visualizations, was that the nature of this experience can make it difficult to draw exact conclusions about certain things. For example, when calculating the pay and tips based on drop off location, it is easy to take this data at face value and believe that delivering to the city of Monroe will provide the best pay. But, in reality there are many factors that play into this that are unseen, especially how much of food was ordered by individuals. The tip for most food delivery apps is defaultly calculated by a percentage of the price of the order. Without these numbers we can not be sure about some of the trends identified in the data, but in respect to the data we have provided there are many trends we have found that are useful to the user and interesting to all.

The most important information we have found has to do with the most important topic:

pay. Our queries have shown the total amounts of money our group member has gained through fare, tips, promotion, and additional amounts. The total pay over all the trips was $5,702.28. This was useful for the sake of understanding the total amount of money that our group member made over this time period, and can be beneficial to those who want a better understanding of the quantity of money that could by being an UberEats driver. More queries dived into information related with highest pay for a trip, what days have the highest payouts on average, and so forth. We learned that when dealing with queries related to money, it is most accurate to take the average of these sums and group them by another variable. Using this method allowed us to more accurately find trends in the data, such as our visualization 1-3. All of these took the average pay and can be used to help predict pay per duration, promotions per day, and average pay per trip. This information is very useful for our group member when strategizing when and where to take his trips, as well as for others to understand how drivers are compensated for their work.
